726507f-a.title: Queens: Dry Harbor Road - Penelope Avenue
726507f-a.text:
Dry Harbor Road, (left not shown), east side, between Penelope
and Sixty-third Avenues, showing the G. Miller house of 1873. J. Miller
had it from 1891-1896. The Estate of G. Miller showed possession
in 1909.
April 1923.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
726507f-a.folder: Dry Harbor Road & Penelope Avenue, Queens, NY

726506f-d.title: Queens: Dry Harbor Road - Penelope Avenue
726506f-d.text:
Dry Harbor Road, west side, north of Penelope Avenue, showing
in two views the Judge Jonathan T. Furman farmhouse from 1852 to 1873.
This house, no longer standing in 1929, is said to have been erected
in 1750. One Monkemeyer was the owner from 1891 to 1912. See other
views.
1922
View 2:April 1923
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

726505f-a.title: Queens: Dry Harbor Road - Penelope Avenue
726505f-a.text:
Dry Harbor Road, west side, north of Penelope Avenue, showing
in three views the J.T. Furman farmhouse. The owner was a former
Sheriff of Queens County. View No. 2 shows in the foreground on
the east side of the Road Feld's Milk Diary. Beyond it in the
background is the Judges home. No.3 is viewed northward.
1922
View 2: May 1923
View 3: April 1923
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726503f-a.title: Queens: Dry Harbor Road - Penelope Avenue
726503f-a.text:
Dry Harbor Road, north from Penelope Avenue, showing (left)
an old farmhouse, which Armbruster believes, questionably,to be
the Wright house of 1873. In 1909 it was owned by Kuhlman.
View 2 shows the same house, at a later date.
View 1: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  April, 1923

726504f-a.title: Queens: Dry Harbor Road - Penelope Avenue
726504f-a.text:
Dry Harbor Road, west side, between Penelope and 63rd Avenues,
showing an old farmhouse, with stuckoed front, which was owned by
M. Kuhlman (Kolmer) in 1909 and 1891. He also owned the house
directly south of this one.
July 2, 1935
P. L. Sperr
